    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3392976194" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3392976194" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3392976194?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/50905990-in-the-penal-colony">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=best-reviews">best-reviews</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3392976194" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1253923923525695618"><b>The story that inspired the Black Quill in &quot;Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix&quot;</b><br/><br/>„In the Penal Colony“ by Kafka is a terrifying und unforgettable short story, full of unlawfulness and inhumanity. A traveler visiting a penal colony, is about to witness the execution of a prisoner. He is introduced to the elaborate torture and execution device, that carves the law, the condemned prisoner has broken, on his skin, before killing him.<br/><br/><b>The Apparatus</b><br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605931923i/30406488._SY540_.jpg' width='500' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><i>Drawing of the torture and execution machine as d</i></span>
  <span id="freeText1253923923525695618" style="display:none"><b>The story that inspired the Black Quill in "Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix"</b><br><br>„In the Penal Colony“ by Kafka is a terrifying und unforgettable short story, full of unlawfulness and inhumanity. A traveler visiting a penal colony, is about to witness the execution of a prisoner. He is introduced to the elaborate torture and execution device, that carves the law, the condemned prisoner has broken, on his skin, before killing him.<br><br><b>The Apparatus</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605931923i/30406488._SY540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Drawing of the torture and execution machine as described</i><br><br>The so called apparatus takes twelve hours to finish an execution, during which the law the prisoner has broken is repeatedly nailed into his flesh. The officer gives an extremely detailed explanation of his beloved device, which he helped to create. The apparatus has three main components, the Bed, the Designer, and the Harrow. By indulging in long, technical descriptions of the machine’s inner-workings, it becomes clear that the officer is more interested in the mechanism’s performance than he is with the prisoners’ fate. The apparatus keeps the prisoner alive by staunching their blood and feeding them, painfully prolonging their death. The workings of the apparatus reinforce the extreme nature and absurdity of capital punishment in a system that does not believe the accuseds life to have any value.<br><br><b>Justice </b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605932166i/30406492.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Methods of the authoritarian legal system</i><br><br>It becomes clear that the prisoner didn’t have a process, but that he was instantly found guilty without a trial, by a high-ranking officer, who automatically assumes that every man who is charged with a crime is guilty. The prisoner doesn’t even know that he is about to be executed and isn‘t told about his sentence until after six hours in the procedure, underscoring the fact that the penal colony’s justice system is unconcerned with protecting or rehabilitating individuals. But the story suddenly turns and becomes even more disturbing, when the traveler is asked to openly express his opinion on the divisive...Ultimately the officer sacrifices himself to the machine, which breaks, suggesting the cruel torture of a justice system that is more concerned with upholding power than it is with the dignity of human life, which is broken and defunct. From critique on a totalitarian and illegal law system, the death penalty, religious interpretations, the First World War, or philosophical and psychological considerations, a variety of possible interpretations are offered. Ultimately the story argues that “justice” used only to maintain power and punish transgressors isn’t really justice at all.<br><br><b> The Prisoner </b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605930041i/30406460._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Franz Kafka - lawyer and writer. Questions of justice permeate all of his works </i><br><br>The prisoner is the most powerless character in the story, illustrating the disparity of power in the penal colony. He is described as stupid and compared to a “submissive dog” that would not try to escape his punishment even if he weren’t tied up. This suggests the dehumanization of the powerless in a society, who are so robbed of dignity and autonomy, what they passively accept. When the workings of the apparatus are explained to the traveler, the prisoner isn‘t even able to understand the object of conversation. He is depicted as child-like, a naive individual who has no capacity for directing his own behavior and needs to be ruled by those in power. The prisoner’s crime is also notably one of disrespecting authority. Therefore it is suggested, that a society built on obeisance to authority above all else, is inherently at odds with the nuance and reason required of genuine justice.<br><br><b> The Black Quill - Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605894354i/30404905._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>The "Black Quill" scaring "I must not tell lies" on Harry‘s hand, while writing with his own blood </i><br><br>It was this story, that inspired J.K Rowling to create Dolores Umbridge‘s „Black quill” in Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix. It‘s a punishing device, where "I must not tell lies" would be inscribed on the hand of the victim through scaring, while they were writing with their own blood instead of ink, causing extreme pain. The officer quite similarly explains that his one principle is that “Guilt is never to be doubted,” any differing opinions would merely be interferences with justice. The prisoner would “have told lies” if he had a chance to defend himself, which consequently just would have been a waste of time, which also explains why he tries to impress the explorer with the intricacies of the apparatus itself rather than with explaining why the apparatus is being used in the first place. If justice intended to prevent future crimes, then the story would suggest that there can be no justice without an understanding of the crime. As such, justice cannot exist in a society in which the punishment is meant solely as a display of power and is more important than the crime or, indeed, than an individual’s life at all. The officer’s sentence and death, in turn, solidifies this idea that any system of justice within the matrix of such strict hierarchical power is faulty. The same principle is used by Dolores Umbridge, who punishes and tortures students without legal basis for telling lies, when they were actually telling the truth, but without chance to defend themselves. Umbridge purposely kept the students in the dark and uneducated about Voldemord‘s return.<br><br><i>“Guilt is never to be doubted.” </i><br><br>This is an extremely thought provoking story. It‘s hard to describe how it made me feel but I found myself torn somewhere between extreme critical thoughts about our legal systems, justice and philosophical meaning, while being quite a bit in shock and horror.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1253923923525695618" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


