<div id="review_2749013967" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2749013967" />
    <a title="Fergus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus"><img alt="Fergus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627838393p2/70395042.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2749013967?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fergus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fergus" href="/user/show/70395042-fergus">Fergus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/44423691-in-the-penal-colony">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2749013967" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4993570740325354378">This is a book for us victims of violence, verbal or otherwise. Cause Kafka shows the TRUE - and truly Horrible - face of our TORMENTORS. <br/><br/>It is a face like that terrifyingly clinical portrait of the brutally cool and poker-faced Nazi War Criminal, Adolf Eichmann, in Hannah Arendt’s chilling Eichmann in Jerusalem. My grandmother gave it to me with the rest of her book collection.<br/><br/>Villains are pretty bland in real life: Like “What - ME worry?”<br/><br/>And like Eichmann, the Commandant of the torture device </span>
  <span id="freeText4993570740325354378" style="display:none">This is a book for us victims of violence, verbal or otherwise. Cause Kafka shows the TRUE - and truly Horrible - face of our TORMENTORS. <br /><br />It is a face like that terrifyingly clinical portrait of the brutally cool and poker-faced Nazi War Criminal, Adolf Eichmann, in Hannah Arendt’s chilling Eichmann in Jerusalem. My grandmother gave it to me with the rest of her book collection.<br /><br />Villains are pretty bland in real life: Like “What - ME worry?”<br /><br />And like Eichmann, the Commandant of the torture device in In the Penal Colony is ONLY DOING HIS JOB.<br /><br />Chilling.<br /><br />I wanted to reread this horrific parable by Kafka one more time- it’s been more than 50 years... So I bought &amp; tried to read this affordable Kindle version.<br /><br />The original story is monumentally sardonic, a lugubriously dark tale about bad guys’ twisted bent - on Ultimate Evil, which in the terror it evokes in us is Beyond Words.<br /><br />I was stupid, and I tried to read this. <br /><br />Horrors. This book was a lame and typo-ridden literal translation of the original version.<br /><br />To put Philip Glass’ name to it is sacrilege. <br /><br />So...<br /><br />If you should, like me, need a quick Kindle copy...<br /><br />WARNING!<br /><br />DO NOT PASS GO on that Kindle monopoly board!<br /><br />DO NOT - REPEAT NOT - BUY THIS.<br /><br />Save your money for much BETTER things!<br /><br />Quite seriously,,,<br /><br />But DO read the original.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4993570740325354378" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


