    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16077597-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582900704p2/16077597.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3468317295?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/16077597-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/38908686-in-der-strafkolonie">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16077597-matt?shelf=hard-rain">hard-rain</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3468317295" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3983305081973410010">Wow. I read a lot of Kafka in my time, but I think I missed this one.<br/><br/>A dystopian chamber play with four actors and a prop, a torture machine fittingly called “the harrow”. And harrowing it is, the exchange between the visitor from a foreign country and the officer who is about to execute the prisoner after a non-trial and for no reason other than he failed to complete an impossible task.<br/><br/>What a fucked up country K. has invented here! We’ve got to be grateful, living in a world in which such blata</span>
  <span id="freeText3983305081973410010" style="display:none">Wow. I read a lot of Kafka in my time, but I think I missed this one.<br><br>A dystopian chamber play with four actors and a prop, a torture machine fittingly called “the harrow”. And harrowing it is, the exchange between the visitor from a foreign country and the officer who is about to execute the prisoner after a non-trial and for no reason other than he failed to complete an impossible task.<br><br>What a fucked up country K. has invented here! We’ve got to be grateful, living in a world in which such blatant abuse of power and inhumanity is unknown, to <em>us</em> as least.<br><br><br><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img alt="Creative Commons License" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380148217i/680962.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>This work is licensed under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/" rel="nofollow noopener">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License</a>.</span>
