<div id="review_1552381887" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1552381887" />
    <a title="Chris_P" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44309339-chris-p"><img alt="Chris_P" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558554241p2/44309339.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1552381887?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris_P" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris_P" href="/user/show/44309339-chris-p">Chris_P</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44309339-chris-p?shelf=classics-and-modern-classics">classics-and-modern-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44309339-chris-p?shelf=shorties">shorties</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1552381887" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15622209568403934217"><i>In the Penal Colony</i> is a short story by Kafka a little different than the others, yet not. There are four characters in the story, each symbolizing his own bit. <b>The Traveler</b> goes to an island to inspect a method of execution carried out by <b>The Officer</b> with the use of a strange, yet elaborate machine. There is also <b>The Condemned Man</b> and <b>The Soldier</b> present. Soon enough the reader realizes that the machine isn&apos;t just a means of execution but rather an inhumane instrument of torture.<br/><br/>I don&apos;t want to</span>
  <span id="freeText15622209568403934217" style="display:none"><i>In the Penal Colony</i> is a short story by Kafka a little different than the others, yet not. There are four characters in the story, each symbolizing his own bit. <b>The Traveler</b> goes to an island to inspect a method of execution carried out by <b>The Officer</b> with the use of a strange, yet elaborate machine. There is also <b>The Condemned Man</b> and <b>The Soldier</b> present. Soon enough the reader realizes that the machine isn't just a means of execution but rather an inhumane instrument of torture.<br /><br />I don't want to write anything else as it is masterful how the details are laid before the reader's eyes. The implications and the symbolisms are countless. Once more I had to bow in front of Kafka's ability to put so much meaning in so few pages and in such a subtle way. One has to experience it in order to understand it. <i>In the Penal Colony</i> is perfectly suitable for discussion and interpretation. Don't expect to close it and forget about it. I finished it last night and I spent almost an hour thinking about it, talking about it with myself (not out loud of course). And <b>that</b> is essential in reading!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15622209568403934217" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


