<div id="review_3685692000" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3685692000" />
    <a title="JimZ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz"><img alt="JimZ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1575257175p2/99765491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3685692000?book_show_action=true">Dec 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JimZ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JimZ" href="/user/show/99765491-jimz">JimZ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3685692000" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14705102455477127679">I’m frustrated because I do not think I came close to understanding a good deal of this novella. When I think of Kafka I think of a great writer. I wonder whether I don’t have the requisite educational background to understand this novella? Or whether I read it too quickly? 🙁<br/><br/>The players in this novella are:<br/>The officer<br/>•	He seems to be judge, jury, and to-be-executioner of the condemned man. There was no trial…after all, according to him, whatever the condemned man was accused of, the condemned ma</span>
  <span id="freeText14705102455477127679" style="display:none">I’m frustrated because I do not think I came close to understanding a good deal of this novella. When I think of Kafka I think of a great writer. I wonder whether I don’t have the requisite educational background to understand this novella? Or whether I read it too quickly? 🙁<br /><br />The players in this novella are:<br />The officer<br />•	He seems to be judge, jury, and to-be-executioner of the condemned man. There was no trial…after all, according to him, whatever the condemned man was accused of, the condemned man would deny it. The officer is the central protagonist in the novella (IMHO)<br />The condemned man<br />•	His crime was falling asleep on the job. He was sentry and every hour on the hour he was to salute the captain’s door at the stroke of each hour. When the captain found him asleep, he lashed the man’s face with his riding crop and the sentry grabbed the captain’s legs and yelled “Throw away that crop, or I’ll eat you alive.” 😲<br />The traveler<br />•	He, a foreigner and visitor to the penal colony, is supposed to be a witness to the execution. However, to him “the injustice of the procedure and the inhumanity of the execution is beyond doubt” and he intends to give that opinion to the current commander after the execution.<br />The captain<br />•	He is described above…he hit the sentry in the face with his riding crop and then reported him to the officer when the sentry threatened to eat him alive. <br />The current commander <br />•	He is not at the to-be-execution and is not a big fan of the proceedings, and may in the near future abolish such proceedings.<br />The past and dead commander <br />•	He was responsible for building the contraption that puts the condemned to death.<br />The soldier <br />•	He keeps guard over the condemned man and plays a small role in the proceedings (IMHO).<br /><br />The description of the contraption is “good” if you are into sadism. It is a machine which writes on the condemned body with needles I think…the ink from the needles used to be mordant (biting)…lots of blood is shed…there is a mouthpiece to muffle the screaming…there are gutters for blood to flow from the body…the body after 12 hours is thrown into a pit and dirt is shoveled into the pit and that is that. The machine slices into the skin of the condemned man, writing the commandment that the condemned man has broken — in this case, ‘Honor thy Superior’. I do believe there are different broken commandments for various executions.<br /><br />On prior days of execution when the past and dead commander was alive, people came to the execution to watch, and children had front row seats at the ghoulish, sadistic proceedings.<br /><br />As I said at the beginning. I don’t think I “got it” …the point of the novella. To wit, several things I did not understand:<br />•	It appears after 6 hours of torture, the person who is being put to death supposedly switches from being in pain (hours 0-6) to being in a state of transfiguration in which he understands fully why he was put to death. I think if I understood what “transfiguration” means maybe I would “get it”. Is this related to the crucifixion of Christ? Does this justify the method of execution? Is the condemned at some point not in pain? Still in pain?<br />•	If the sentry had accepted the lash to the face, would the sentry then not have been condemned to death, or was falling asleep on the job an executable offense?<br />•	<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ When the officer switched positions with the condemned man so that now he was in the grips of the contraption, why was the commandment “Be Just” written on his body? Was this a commandment that the officer had broken? Again, this was clearly over my head…as was the botched result in which apparently the officer near death was not transfigured (“…no sign of the promised redemption was perceptible’ the officer had not found what all the others had found in the machine”). The officer was impaled on the needles or his head was impaled on a spike…I‘m not sure which or maybe both. “This was no torture, it was full-blown murder.” Wait a minute…I thought what upset the traveler was his opinion that the whole process was torture and murder.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> 🤨<br /><br />I am going to rate this as 2.4 stars and doing the rounding this comes down to 2 stars. 😑 I need to be faithful to my rating system and the Goodreads rating system. Whatever bottom line or lines I was supposed to get, I didn’t get it. That could be my fault…I don’t know.<br /><br />After I write this review I will go to Wikipedia, and to other GR reviewers, and see what I missed.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14705102455477127679" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


