<div id="review_276201925" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/276201925" />
    <a title="Abdel-Rahman El-Naggar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7717596-abdel-rahman-el-naggar"><img alt="Abdel-Rahman El-Naggar" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1329025162p2/7717596.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/276201925?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abdel-Rahman El-Naggar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abdel-Rahman El-Naggar" href="/user/show/7717596-abdel-rahman-el-naggar">Abdel-Rahman El-Naggar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer276201925" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8176996444160227367">I can&apos;t believe I actually respected the Officer by the end of the story. While his beliefs are purely evil, if you can ever call anything purely evil, he stayed committed to them to the very end. He even died to prove his point. I loved that. The Condemned, on whose side we were in the beginning of the story, turned out to be.. umm.. a bastard. The Officer did forgive him, but when places changed, the Condemned failed to give forgiveness back to the Officer. Maybe he wasn&apos;t aware that he was fo</span>
  <span id="freeText8176996444160227367" style="display:none">I can't believe I actually respected the Officer by the end of the story. While his beliefs are purely evil, if you can ever call anything purely evil, he stayed committed to them to the very end. He even died to prove his point. I loved that. The Condemned, on whose side we were in the beginning of the story, turned out to be.. umm.. a bastard. The Officer did forgive him, but when places changed, the Condemned failed to give forgiveness back to the Officer. Maybe he wasn't aware that he was forgiven 'cause he wasn't aware that he was guilty in the first place, but this does not justify the way he acted when he had the power. As for the Traveler, we have all been in his place once or twice in our lives.. a place where nothing makes sense, no matter how hard you try to figure it out. It's such a challenge, probably to everything you believe in, to be asked, not only to watch non-sense, but to actually confirm and support it, as well. The Traveler was too shy, he never made a change until the officer stepped back and granted him the chance to make a change.. the POWER to make a change. Ahhhh, everything revolves around power and the way you exercise it. In the past, people loved the machine and wouldn't miss a chance to watch a human soul being murdered inside of it. That's how the previous Commandant exercised his own power. But now that the Commandant is dead, it's not the golden age of the machine anymore, so the officer suddenly sounds weird. It's a pity you have to wait for enough people, with enough power, to disapprove of something in order for it to become WRONG.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8176996444160227367" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


