<div id="review_2839815794" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2839815794" />
    <a title="Numidica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62390164-numidica"><img alt="Numidica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1585183805p2/62390164.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2839815794?book_show_action=true">May 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Numidica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Numidica" href="/user/show/62390164-numidica">Numidica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2839815794" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17282651670714993474">A short book (really a short story) by Kafka which is an allegory of Europe moving from rigid, often unjust, punishment for minor offenses toward the more liberal society of the &quot;present&quot;. Since it was written in 1914, Kafka had no way of knowing how vigorously the old draconian system would revive, if only for twelve years, in the form of national socialism under Hitler. But ultimately his allegory proved mostly correct.</span>
  <span id="freeText17282651670714993474" style="display:none">A short book (really a short story) by Kafka which is an allegory of Europe moving from rigid, often unjust, punishment for minor offenses toward the more liberal society of the "present". Since it was written in 1914, Kafka had no way of knowing how vigorously the old draconian system would revive, if only for twelve years, in the form of national socialism under Hitler. But ultimately his allegory proved mostly correct.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17282651670714993474" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
